@ENDNODE
@NODE Errors "Super-DupeCheck: Error Messages."
	Below is a list of all of the error messages output by
Super-DupeCheck when something goes wrong. I hope that this information
will help you solve whatever problem you are having. If not, try and get
in contact with me!

	All error messages not listed here are standard AmigaDOS error
messages and are ususall connected to the loading in of files and allocation
of memory. These messages should be more or less self-explanatory.
	For example, if the util aborts saying "out of memory" and also
telling you a filename, it was probably trying to allocate some memory to
load the file, but there was not enough.
	If the util aborts saying "file not found" then you have probably
not set something up correctly as the util is looking for a file that is
not on your harddrive (again, the filename it is looking for should be
given to you by the util).



Internal Error:
	Internal errors should never (hopefully) be encountered.
Basically, I have put some checks within my code that make sure that
strange things are not happening. These things should never happen, but
just incase they do, I have included routines which will abort the util
without crashing your machine.
	If you get an internal error, it is probably not your fault,
and you should try and report what happened to me so that I can fix
whatever is causing the problem.


Buffer Overflow:
	You will get a buffer overflow error if the util encounters
something which is unexpectedly long (ooeerr!). I have allowed for quite
long strings in most cases, but it is always possible that there is someone
out there who likes to have paths consisting of three million characters...

	Things such as the User's name and access level, the paths to
conferences and files, and the length of the filename to be checked all have
length restrictions. However, the util supports things as long, and sometimes
longer, as AmiExpress does, so you shouldn't have any problems.
	If you do get a Buffer Overflow message, load out your config script
and have a look for any really long lines -> they're probably the problem.



Error in Config Script:
	This tells you that there is a problem with the config script
(SDupeChk.cfg). The error message tells you the line number of where
the problem appears to be, as well as the path to the problematic script.

	There are three main reasons why you will get this error message:
1) You have used a command not recognised by Super-DupeCheck.
2) You have forgotten to put a return at the end of the line (remember the
   return on the last line of the file!).
3) You have given a command an invalid argument. (For example, the argument
   is too long (similar to a Buffer Overflow error), or is the wrong type
   (for example, the command expects a number and you give it the name of
   a door to run), or is in the wrong range (for example, the commands
   that expect a numerical argument will only accept numbers between 0 and
   9 or 0 and 99, depending on the command).

Others:
	If the program tells you that there are 99 dir files in a conference
(i.e. it says something like "Checking in Conference Directory 2 of 99") it
is because it was unable to find out the conference's value of "NDirs" and
has defaulted to using 99. This does no harm apart from looking a little
strange, because the util stops at the first dir it cannot find anyway.
	Currently, the util will look for NDirs in two places (in order):
1) BBS:<CONF_PATH>.info   (The tooltype "NDirs=???") This is for /X-3
2) BBS:<CONF_PATH>/NDirs  (Whatever number is in the file)   for /X-2
	Perhaps the way that the NDirs is specified will change in the
future (in the next update of /X you'll probably have to specify the number
by taking the number of dirs, adding 42, multiplying by 3 and saving the
result to a file called "DF0:Stupid_Ideas_And_Bad_Design"), in which case
you can either put up with it saying "99", wait for an update (if I do one),
or create an NDirs file for all your conferences (like everyone who went to
/X-3 had to do for some of the older NewFiles doors, 'coz they didn't think
that it would be usefull to be able to access ALL of the information about
the BBS setup through the poorly designed /X door-port).
@ENDNODE
