@NODE Others_OTHERS "Super-DupeCheck: Other Releases, Misc."
=============================================================================
:::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::
=============================================================================

Some of these things are totally useless...
...some have been superceded...
...some are quite usefull but not big enough to be a release in their own
   right (often these are included as bonus tools with other programs)...
...some have been custom coded for total cunts who don't want them released
   because they want their BBS to look special instead of P0T-NOoDLE to be
   more famous (sheeze! DAMM YOU! GROW SOME! THROUGH STRAWS!).

...(I didn't touch her)...


-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
P0T-FONTS.LHA - The Amazing, Beautiful P0T-NOoDLE fonts! To replace those
                boring ones on your workbench! Proportional version as well!
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
AmiLog                - The original last callers util, coded by Retaliator
(68000) by Retaliator - and Designed by P0T-NOoDLE way back in '91.
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
Super-Mutherfuckin-Secure - Our Private BBS security System.
(68000) by P0T-NOoDLE     - Only given to a few friends.
                          - Consists of various independant modules.
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
<Unnamed>             - A FrontEnd door that shows a logon text and waits
(68000) by P0T-NOoDLE - for the user to type "Y". If they type "N", they
                      - are chucked off the BBS. If they type "R" they are
                      - shown the System rules. Given to people on request,
                      - but not really worth publicly releasing!
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
Guru                  - A Util that crashed your Amiga. Not released b'coz
(68000) by P0T-NOoDLE - it's a bit useless really!
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
View/View_Sysop Doors - Lets users view text files, but only if they are
(Arexx) by P0T-NOoDLE - smaller than the sysop defined length.
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
T.A.S ]I[             - An archive tester (and once adder, before I got sick
(ARexx & 68000) b P0T - of my BBS adds!) that does everything offline.
                      - Includes random add logos, auto-FreeDownload flagging
                      - T.A.S was the VERY FIRST offline adder/checker for /X
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
Super-Chuck-Up-Nudel-Node-Nuke - A quicky to nuke callers on other nodes!
(ARexx)                        - written whilst on the phone to Picard and
                               - Hydro. Additional crap ripped by Picard!hhe
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
Mr.SelfDestruct - Custom Self-Extracting Archiver for G'G Utils.
(68000)
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
(Super)Ped Pager - ASM Conversion of Picard's ARexx Sysop page door
(68000)
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
Super-Scrambled-Eggs - A poor-man's "encryption". A tool to quickly render
(68000)              - something like a GIF/JPG/IFF picture unviewable, but
                     - reversable.
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
M-Strip - A door for Sigma-Express to Strip ^M's from file_id.diz files.
(68000)
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
Super-Billiards - A program for P0T-NOoDLE's "A"-level maths investigation.
(68000)
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
DayRunner - A program to be run in (logoff) batch files which ensures a
(68000)     script is run once a day, at most. (Included with some utils)
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
DelDir - A script to go through an /X file dir and, for each file, show its
(ARexx)  description and ask to leave it, move it to another path, delete it.
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
AnswerReader - A door slapped together to search for and display a given
(68000)        user's entry in the BBS:NodeXX/Answers file.
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
Super-DropOff - Drops carrier on a user, usefull as a turbo-logoff command.
(68000)
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
Super-PissOff - A logoff door with (optionally anonymous) message to next usr
(68000)
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
Super-Widget, Turbo Professional NT - Sends a text file to the user.
(68000)                             - Can send different to PC & Amiga users.
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
Download Mania - Installs over the D command and when someone tries to
(68000)          download, it will only let them if they are in a list of
                 excluded users, or if they are within the download-allowed
                 time. There are TWO different download-allowed times which
                 you can configure so that different people are able to
                 download during different periods (eg normal after 7pm,
                 leechers after 8pm, and cool people anytime).
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
Super-Page NT Pro IV Deluxe GTi Plus - A pager door which looks so good, it's
(68000)                                a crime. Asks for a chat reason,
                                       stored in the callerslog, and flashes
the sysop's screens while paging with a nice percentage-done bar. User can
retry twice, leave a comment, or give up. User CAN abort during paging.
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
...and probably others I forgot!
Ask one of us if you are interested in anything!
=============================================================================
:::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::
=============================================================================
@ENDNODE
@NODE SDirStrip "Super-DupeCheck: Super-DirStrip Support Program."
                    .----------------------------------.
          .---------' Super-DirStrip v1.01 [RELEASE 1] `---------.
          | Written by P0T-NOoDLE of ANTHR0X, (C)1994 Gods'Gift. |
          `------------------------------------------------------'
RELEASED    ..::::::.`-. For Super-DupeCheck v1.03+ .-' .::::.:.
with Super-DupeCheck:: `----------------------------' .::.:'..'

Purpose:
	To create stripped-down directory listings, as described in the
section on @{" Global-Dupe-Dirs " LINK Dir_G}.
	Put simply, stripped-down listings contain only the filenames
of what has been uploaded, without any description etc. This means that
the files are much smaller and thus take less time to dupecheck and
waste less harddrive space.
	Directories stripped down using this util are converted to
upper-case so that you can use the slightly faster dupecheck routines
(see the @{" `Check' " LINK Check} command...).

	SDirStrip is able to convert listings to a format compatible
with the NastyDupCheck method of dupe-checking. For more information,
see the section on @{" Hints and Warnings " LINK SDDHAW} for Stripped-Dir-Files.

	A good idea is to convert all of your existing directories into
stripped-down listings and have Super-DupeCheck check ONLY these. (You
can do this by specifying the stripped-down listing as an external file
and setting the highest dir number to zero with the @{" `HiDi:' " LINK HiDi} command).
You can then use the @{" `StDr:' " LINK StDr} and @{" `StIn:' " LINK StIn} commands to have the names
of all files uploaded automatically added to the stripped-down list.
	One nice thing which you can do is to join up all your listings
into one large one, and have the @{" `StDr:' " LINK StDr} set the same for all
conferences so that all conferences are cross-checked, quickly!

	In addition to this, there is another support program called
@{" Super-DirAdd " LINK SDirAdd} which can make updating your stripped-down dir files
much easier (for example, in conjunction with DirectoryOpus, etc).


ReadArgs template:

FROM/K/A,TO/K/A,INCINFO/S,NEW/S


   From: Specify the filename of the dir to be stripped-down.
         Must be specified.

     To: Specify the filename to write the stripped-down dir to.
         If this file already exists, it will be appended to.
         Must be specified.

IncInfo: If you give this option, the filesize and date will be left in
         the stripped-down version so that when a user uploads a file
         that gets duped they know a little bit more about it.

    New: If you give this option and the TO file already exists,
         instead of appending to it, it will be overwritten.


For Example:

SDirStrip From BBS:Amiga/Dir1 To BBS:STDir IncInfo

Will read in "BBS:Amiga/Dir1" and strip it down, appending the output to
"BBS:STDir" (or creating a new file if it doesn't exist), and including
the filesize and date of uploading.


	Sorry that this program is so slow, but you only have to run it
once, so it shouldn't be too much of a pain. I used the FGets() read call
to parse the input filename which meant coding was much easier, but also
meant that it runs quite slowly! I didn't think it was worth coding a
special routine like that found in Super-DupeCheck itself for such a simple
util!...

History: v1.01 - First release, included with SDupeCheck v1.03
@ENDNODE
@NODE SDirAdd "Super-DupeCheck: Super-DirAdd Support Program."
                     .--------------------------------.
          .----------' Super-DirAdd v1.00 [RELEASE 1] `----------.
          | Written by P0T-NOoDLE of ANTHR0X, (C)1994 Gods'Gift. |
          `------------------------------------------------------'
RELEASED    ..::::::.`-. For Super-DupeCheck v1.03+ .-' .::::.:.
with Super-DupeCheck:: `----------------------------' .::.:'..'

Purpose:
	To update stripped-down directory listings, as described in the
section on @{" Global-Dupe-Dirs " LINK Dir_G}.
	Put simply, stripped-down listings contain only the filenames
of what has been uploaded, without any description etc. This means that
the files are much smaller and thus take less time to dupecheck and
waste less harddrive space.
	Entire directories can be stripped-down using the other support
util, @{" Super-DirStrip " LINK SDirStrip}.

	Stripped-down dir files created with either support program are
converted to upper-case so that you can use the slightly faster dupecheck
routines (see the @{" `Check' " LINK Check} command...).

	You should see the section on @{" Hints and Warnings " LINK SDDHAW} for
Stripped-Dir-Files.

	Super-DirAdd works similarly to the @{" `StDr:' " LINK StDr} command, except it
works from DOS, not from the Super-DupeCheck door. You give Super-DirAdd
a filename and it adds it to a specified stripped-down dir file in the
correct format. Althought I'm sure people will find others, the main
purpose behind Super-DirAdd is to make it easy for people to setup a
button in a program such as DirectoryOpus where they can select one or
more files and click on the button to have all the files moved or deleted
while at the same time their names are added to the stripped-down list so
that the files cannot be uploaded again (phew what a sentense!).


ReadArgs template:

FN=FILENAME/K/A,DF=DIRFILE/K/A


  Filename: Specify the name of the file to be added to the dir.
            You ONLY give the name, NO PATHS or anything else!
            AmiExpress listings are limited to 12char filenames.
            FN can be used for short.
            Must be specified.

   DirFile: Specify the name and path to the stripped-down dir file to be
            added to. If the file doesn't already exist, it will be
            created (if it already exists, it'll be appended to).
            DF can be used for short.
            Must be specified.

For Example:

SDirAdd Filename ATX-SDC1.EXE DirFile BBS:STDir

Will add "ATX-SDC1.EXE" to the stripped-down dir file "BBS:STDir"



Installation into DirOpus:

 If you want to setup a button that will add the selected files to the
stripped-down dir listing and then delete them, configure a button with
the following (replacing "BBS:STDir" with whatever you want)...


  AmigaDOS    BBS:Utils/SDirAdd FN {ou} DF BBS:STDir
  AmigaDOS    Delete {f} FORCE


 The following flags ONLY should be turned ON:
  Do all files
  Reload each file
  Rescan source

A graphic-snap of the config-screen should be included in the distribution
archive which should make things a bit clearer.



History: v1.00 - First release, included with SDupeCheck v1.03

TO DO: Optionally add filesize and date as well
       (like @{" SDirStrip " LINK SDirStrip} and @{" `StDr:' " LINK StDr} do already).
       This util was a bit of a rush job and I just don't have enough time
       to code any more of it...
@ENDNODE
@NODE SDDHAW "Super-DupeCheck: Hints and Tips on Stripped-Down Dir-Listings"
	These hints also apply to global-dupe-dirs. For more information
on stripped-down dir-listings and global-dupe-dirs, see the following
sections:
 @{" Global-dupe-dirs " LINK Dir_G}.
 The @{" `StDr:' " LINK StDr} and @{" `StIn:' " LINK StIn} commands.
 The @{" Super-DirStrip " LINK SDirStrip} support-util docs.
 The @{" Super-DirAdd " LINK SDirAdd} support-util docs.


	Of course, if you do use stripped-down dir-listings, don't forget
to have Super-DupeCheck actually perform a dupe-check using them!!
See the @{" `DirF:' " LINK DirF} command for information on how to do this.


--[1]----------------------------------------------------------------------
	The NastyDupCheck method (all credit for the idea to VideoNasty. I
hope he does not mind me including his ideas in these docs):
	Maintain a stripped-down dir listing containing only filenames and
specify this with the FILESNOTALLOWED=<pathname> tooltype in the NodeX.info
icon (or in the ACP.STARTUP for those using /X 2.xx).
	With this method installed you can disable all other types of
dupechecking (you need not even include the @{" Check: " LINK Check} command!).
	This  method  will mean that dupe files will be detected as soon as
the BBS receives the name of the file about to be uploaded.  This means
that dupes will NEVER be uploaded (they'll be stopped before the upload
begins).
	For the user it means that they'll never lose time or credits
because they uploaded a dupe. (VideoNasty adds that the user also doesn't
have to wait for a DupeChecker to finish checking the DirX files. However,
I seriously doubt that the search routine which AmiExpress uses on the
FilesNotAllowed file is anywhere near as fast as most DupeCheckers - it's
written in `C' by someone who isn't exactly regarded for being a coding
god, after all. This said, I've never tested AmiExpress with a
FilesNotAllowed large enough to have any idea of how fast the routine is).
	For the sysop it means that they don't have to waste time dealing
with dupes.

	Once again, all credit and respect for this go to VideoNasty.
I would not have even included this idea had I not already written the
routines which make SDupeCheck capable of this type of dupe-checking.
However, since I had, I thought I might as well include the information
on how to use them in this way (nothing was coded with this idea in
mind, it's just luck that the new commands can be applied in this way
which I had never even thought of before).
See also [2], [3], and [4] 

--[2]----------------------------------------------------------------------
	If you use the NastyDupCheck method, make sure that you do NOT turn
on any options which include more information than just the filename in
stripped-dirs. This means making sure that the @{" `StIn:' " LINK StIn} command is set to
"NO" for the @{" `StDr:' " LINK StDr} command, and the `IncInfo' swicth is NOT included in
the commandline for @{" Super-DirStrip " LINK SDirStrip}.
	AmiExpress will probably not recognize filenames in a filenames-
not-allowed file if it has lots of stuff tacked on after the names
themselves! (...and even if it does, the extra info would be a waste of
space because noone would ever see it!).

--[3]----------------------------------------------------------------------
	You must remember that Super-DupeCheck is run BEFORE files are
tested. While with /X3+ Super-DupeCheck can detect private uploads, there
is no way for it to detect whether a file is going to fail its test or not.
Because of this, all filenames will be added to stripped-down dir-files
by the  `StDr:'  command.
	This is not that great: if a file fails the test and is then sent
to the hold dir, someone may come along with an OK version of the file with
the same name, try to upload it, and be told it's a dupe! Because of this,
if you use a Stripped-down dir-file you must make sure that all failed
files are removed from it.
	I cannot think of any way around this, so you will have to make up
your own mind whether or not you want to use it!
	On the other hand, if you get hold of NastyDupCheck, it does
provide a way to do this (and only this) so that failed uploads are NOT
added to the list. You could use this method using the @{" SDirAdd " LINK SDirAdd} util
which is included with SDupeCheck instead of the AddFile.Rexx which
comes with NastyDupCheck (it's only a matter of setting up some DOS
scripts, but I don't want to re-invent the wheel - get NastyDupCheck if
you're interested - if you have half a brain and know enough about
AmigaDOS and AmiExpress (which all sysops fuckin' should!) you should
be able to combine the two packages).

--[4]----------------------------------------------------------------------
	This applies to people using NastyDupCheck as well...
	If you have something like a members' conf where stuff to be spread
is uploaded and moved to another conf at a later date, you must make sure
that files uploaded to this conf are NOT added to dir-files checked by
other conferences. This is quite easy to do using different config files
for different conferences (by the way, this is not possible with the
NastyDupCheck method because AmiExpress uses the same FilesNotAllowed file
for all conferences.)
@ENDNODE
@NODE History "Super-DupeCheck: Program History."
Super-DupeCheck History.
Only actually released versions are shown (all changes done in Beta Versions
are counted as changes to the next release). Lastest Versions at the END.


.=[*][*][*][*][*][*][*][*][*][*][*][*][*][*][*][*][*][*][*][*][*][*][*][*]=.
[*] Version v1.00 [====] Release #01 [=====] Released on 2nd April, 1994 [*]
`=[*][*][*][*][*][*][*][*][*][*][*][*][*][*][*][*][*][*][*][*][*][*][*][*]='
----------------------------------------------------------------------------
Changes:
None, Initial Release.
----------------------------------------------------------------------------
Things To Do: (If I get some motiviating letters!)
1) Add ability to automatically filecomment files for free-download if their
   filenames match a certain pattern. (For Example you could have all files
   of the form "ATX-#?" made free-downloads).
2) I'm open to suggestions!
----------------------------------------------------------------------------
Known Bugs:
1) I have not been able to get anything like this to happen at my end, but
   Kool Falco tells me that a (Rexx) door he tried to use with Super-DupeChk
   always failed and caused my program to get into an endless loop, showing
   the same text file over and over again. I have no idea why this should
   happen, but if you should experience this, or any other problem please
   get in contact with me as if there is a bug I would like to track it down
   and remove it!
----------------------------------------------------------------------------
.=[*][*][*][*][*][*][*][*][*][*][*][*][*][*][*][*][*][*][*][*][*][*][*][*]=.
[*] Version v1.01 [====] Release #02 [=====] Released on 4th April, 1994 [*]
`=[*][*][*][*][*][*][*][*][*][*][*][*][*][*][*][*][*][*][*][*][*][*][*][*]='
----------------------------------------------------------------------------
Brief: Filecheckers in the FCheck dir/icon will now run with the door.
----------------------------------------------------------------------------
Changes:
1) Last night I got a reports from Kool Falco and Amok that the standard
   internal FileCheck doors (those in FCheck) were not being run after my
   door had been run. This was wierd to me because Hydro and Dream Warrior
   have got the FCheck doors running fine, and noone had ever noticed it
   before (I haven't thouched that bit of code for ages). Anyway, I checked
   it out myself on my little test-BBS and sure enough the reports were
   correct. I'm now putting +2 into JH_Data for the GoodFile call which
   appears to work! (Thanx to Amok's friend for telling me the number!).
   I'd like to point out that this problem would never had happened had the
   AmiExpress docs been written a bit better and less ambiguous! (The /X docs
   never fucking properly describe anything, and they don't even mention
   that +2 is a valid number for JH_Data on that call! (Hell maybe it isn't
   and my code is totally wrong, but anyway it works!)). Sorry for the
   problem, and a big thanx for the guys mentioned for the quick report!
   PS: I think that it was working for some people because they were running
   stuff like BigBoss' server that (I assume) set the GoodFile thing after
   the Check command has been run.
2) On Trash City DupeCheck Guru'd due to a Divide-by-zero. I didn't think
   that this would ever happen as there is only one place in the entire
   program where there is a divide that doesn't use immediate data. I can't
   see how that routine produced the error, but I've put a little check in
   that should stop it guruing.
3) Removed about 5 lines of code that didn't need to be there anymore.
----------------------------------------------------------------------------
.=[*][*][*][*][*][*][*][*][*][*][*][*][*][*][*][*][*][*][*][*][*][*][*][*]=.
[*] Version v1.02 [====] Release #03 [====] Released on 10th August 1994 [*]
`=[*][*][*][*][*][*][*][*][*][*][*][*][*][*][*][*][*][*][*][*][*][*][*][*]='
----------------------------------------------------------------------------
Brief: Added Automatic Free-Download Flagging.
       Now shows the file-description of the file when a dupe is found.
       Now you can tell the program exactly what dir files to check in for
          dupes by giving their full path. Even dir files from other
          conferences can be scanned.
       Now possible to specify the Lowest directory to check, awa highest.
       Slight speed optimizations.
       Better, more informative error messages.
       Special '020+ code.
       No longer is there a BBS add in the output.
       New output - much more sexy!
----------------------------------------------------------------------------
****************** This program is now Charity-Ware! ***********************
	I know that most you out there won't pay anything at all, but I am
doing this in the hope that at least a few people donate even a small amount
of money, because every little penny can be put to some good!
	Please, at least read about the charity, @{" Children of the Storm " LINK Charity}.
I not going to say that anyone who doesn't send off some money should feel
really guilty, just that anyone who does send off some money should feel
really great, knowing that they've helped someone out.
	Even if you don't want to send any money (for whatever reasons),
you could always send a letter of support, or spread the word to other
people.
----------------------------------------------------------------------------
Changes:
1) Docs updated for new features of this release (see below points).
2) Now uses my lastest DOS and Data Handling routines as developed for
   @{" Super-AmiLog III " LINK InfoSAL} (Comming soon(ish)).
3) Some slight optimizations (nothing noticable) to the general code.
   Thanks to 2-Cool for pointing the SF command's virtue. (See @{" greets " LINK Greets}).
4) Added @{" `LoDi' " LINK LoDi} command for specifying the lowest dir to be checked.
   This, together with the old @{" `HiDi' " LINK HiDi}, allow you to specify any range of
   dirs. (Eg check all dirs from Dir3 to Dir11 or whatever). I thought of
   this while coding v1.00, but I didn't think anyone would want it. I was
   wrong, as Spread requested this feature. (Thanks for the feedback,
   finally: here's the update!)
5) Better error reports when something goes wrong. Previously almost any
   error not connected with loading a file would be reported as an
   "internal error", which is not much help. Now, the messages are a bit
   more specific, and if the problem is something to do with the Config
   Script, you are told the line number where the problem appears to be.
   See new section of the docs: @{" Error Messages " LINK Errors}.
6) No longer gives aborts with an "internal error" when given a really
   small dir (i.e. one with no file descriptions in at all!) to check.
7) There is now special code in SDupeCheck for people with a 68020 or
   higher which replaces the utility.library 32-bit division routine by
   the 68020+'s built in instruction. This should result in a little bit
   more speed. There program will auto-detect your CPU and use the code
   designed for it. Thanks to Thrash for the '020 detect code.
8) Changed the outout slightly. No longer mentions any BBS names so that
   I don't have to make people custom versions and so that people who
   think that a BBS name being on a util will kill their cat or something
   may consider running the util. (Sheeze, some people don't wanna run an
   otherwise cool util because of a tiny BBS add?? I hope none of you dicks
   went and altered the message without knowing what you were doing...).
9) Added the automatic @{" free-download command " LINK Free} that I had originally
   intended for v1.00 but never bothered to put in. Currently it only
   looks at file prefixes and doesn't support proper wildcards, but it
   should do the job that most of you guys want. If I get any requests, I
   might improve the @{" `Free:' " LINK Free} command to fully support wildcards.
10) When a dupe is found the file description of it is shown to the user.
    This has been requested by lot of people, so here it is now!
11) It is now possible to tell the @{" `Check' " LINK Check} command to look in given
    directories. To do this you give it the path(s) to your dir-files using
    the @{" `DirF:' " LINK DirF} command. This allows you to easily have dupechecks
    performed accross conferences.
12) Some exciting (!) animations have been added (meaning the main file is
    an extra 4k long!! but who cares?). While they are all reasonably short
    and shouldn't cause any problems, there is a new command - @{" `Anim:' " LINK Anim} -
    which allows boring sysops to disable the animated text (perhaps it
    could cause some problems with really bad lines or something).
13) The program is now more descriptive about which directory it is looking
    in. The type of directory is now stated (e.g. External Dir, Global Dir)
    and, where applicable, the number of the dir, along with how many dirs
    there are in total, is shown.
14) Because of change #13, the NDirs file/tooltype is now examined.
15) Guide now has an Index (use the button up there!!).
16) It is now possible to have all duped files that are moved to the hold
    dir replaced by a small file-comment so that they don't take up as much
    room on your harddrive. To enable or disable this, use the new @{" `Kill:' " LINK Kill}
    command.
17) When a duped file is sent to the hold dir, a message is now placed
    before its file description saying that it is a dupe (so that you know
    it's there because it's a dupe, and not because it failed a CRC check or
    something). Unfortunately, it is not easy to append this message to the
    file's description (as the door is run after the file description has
    been processed), and the way that the message is added before the file
    description means that if you do a new-scan on your hold dir and a
    duped file is at the top of the list, you may not be shown the message.
18) Fixed a bug where the @{" cross-archive-checking " LINK CAC} would only work if the
    filename was given in uppercase.
19) Output totally redesigned! Now it looks really sexy!
----------------------------------------------------------------------------
Things To Do: (If I get some motiviating letters!)
1) Improve the @{" `Free:' " LINK Free} command to fully support wilcard patterns instead
   of its currently limited prefix-only system.
2) I'm still open to suggestions!
----------------------------------------------------------------------------
.=[*][*][*][*][*][*][*][*][*][*][*][*][*][*][*][*][*][*][*][*][*][*][*][*]=.
[*] Version v1.03 [====] Release #04 [====] Released on xxth xxxxxx 199x [*]
`=[*][*][*][*][*][*][*][*][*][*][*][*][*][*][*][*][*][*][*][*][*][*][*][*]='
----------------------------------------------------------------------------
 1) Fixed a problem in the AmigaGuide docs: the node about the @{" `Kill' " LINK Kill}
    command was labelled incorrectly as the node about the  `LoDi'  command,
    which was labelled OK. This meant that references to  `Kill'  failed to
    work, and references to  `LoDi'  went to the  `Kill'  node. It also
    explains why the Browse buttons stopped working half way through the
    guide: because there were two nodes named the same! (I thought it was
    just a bug in AmigaGuide). So many problems for such a little thing!
  - This was detected using CheckGuide v1.0 by Eddy Carroll. Great tool!
 2) Wrote the @{" Super-DirStrip " LINK SDirStrip} support program, which you should have found
    included with this version of Super-DupeCheck. This program can be used
    to strip down directory listings to save HD space and speed up
    dupechecking.
 3) Added the ability for Super-DupeCheck to automatically maintain a
    stripped down directory listing (such as that created by @{" S-DirStrip " LINK SDirStrip}).
    The new script commands to control how this is done are @{" `StIn:' " LINK StIn} and
    @{" `StDr:' " LINK StDr}.
  - Thanks to MDR at Cement City BBS for feedback and requesting (2) & (3).
 4) Because of (3), it is now possible to use this program like
    NastyDupCheck by Video Nasty (all credits for the idea to him) by having
    @{" `StDr:' " LINK StDr} maintain the FileNames-Not-Allowed file.
    See notes on the @{" `StDr:' " LINK StDr} command for more info.
 5) The last command at the end of the script file may have previously been
    interpreted as being invalid due to having no return at the end when,
    in fact, it did. Fixed.
 6) When a dupe is detected and sent to the hold dir, the message added to
    the hold dir will now always been seen when you do a scan using "N S H"
    because it now looks like another file to AmiExpress.
 7) Improved detection of 68020 or above. Previously it *MAY* have used the
    slightly slower 68000 routines on '030s and '040s (big deal).
 8) Added @{" `FSze:' " LINK FSze} command which allows you to limit the size of free-
    downloads.
  - Thanks to Ice D at Burger Bar BBS for the idea.
 9) Stripped dirs now only require minimum line length of 14 chars:
    A return at the end, upto 12 chars for the filename, and one or
    more spaces inbetween the two. See the output produced by
    @{" S-DirStrip " LINK SDirStrip}.
----------------------------------------------------------------------------
Things To Do:
1) Looks like noone wanted propper wildcards in the `Free:' command, so I
   won't add that.
2) Possibly add a turbo-dupe-check mode for stripped-down dir-listings.
@ENDNODE
@REMARK Release dates to be filled in History, Other-Utils, Main, and Version string at the top.

Update the index.
Update the Example Config File.

Add GameBoy msg from SSel (!).

Note that StDr: will not add if it's DETECTED as a private upload.
 If you're running /X 2 I don't think it'll be able to detect private
 uploads because the file_id.diz code that wasn't added until /X 3 and
 that code makes the file-description accessible to the filecheck
 programs. (/X is so lame that there is no intended method for knowing
 whether a file is a private upload or not, utils have to read the
 file-description from the Work/ directory and check for a "/", and
 in /X 2 the file-description is only in the Work/ directory if the
 user entered the description before uploading).
 I'm not sure about compatability with Sigma-Express, I have a feeling
 that it should work, but you better test whether Super-DupeCheck
 notices private uploads on your own system!

